    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1534607417" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1534607417" />
    <a title="Kylie Gillis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5764569-kylie-gillis"><img alt="Kylie Gillis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366440065p2/5764569.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1534607417?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kylie Gillis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kylie Gillis" href="/user/show/5764569-kylie-gillis">Kylie Gillis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/16070942-the-samurai-s-garden">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1534607417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4622971022462973384">What is it about Japanese books that soothe the soul so well? The clean, bare rooms with tatami mats, kneeling for tea, the simple meals of rice and pickled vegetables, the good, pure joy of things being simple and beautiful in a quiet and understated way. I can&apos;t get enough of this kind of book. And these things are physical representations of the writing itself which is clean, simple, elegant, and real. I&apos;m not finished reading the book yet, but it is completely engaging as it allows me to sli</span>
  <span id="freeText4622971022462973384" style="display:none">What is it about Japanese books that soothe the soul so well? The clean, bare rooms with tatami mats, kneeling for tea, the simple meals of rice and pickled vegetables, the good, pure joy of things being simple and beautiful in a quiet and understated way. I can't get enough of this kind of book. And these things are physical representations of the writing itself which is clean, simple, elegant, and real. I'm not finished reading the book yet, but it is completely engaging as it allows me to slip away from my world of clutter and bright colours and stress and spend some time in a Japanese garden contemplating the beauty of life and people. <br /><br />Set in the 1930s during the Japanese attach on China, this book nevertheless feels timeless. As its protagonist, Stephen, heals his body, I join him in his retreat, healing my mind. This is also one of the first Japanese books I have read that is set near the ocean, and that lends something even more relaxing and healing to the book. A retreat within Japan, which is itself a retreat from the consumerism and superficiality of the Western world. I think this book is like a haiku. It stills my soul and brings me peace.<br /><br />***<br /><br />I finished it now, and found this video which I would recommend to anyone who was wondering exactly what Japan looked like in the 1930s. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A4fkX1SVT0A">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A4fkX...</a> </span>
  <a data-text-id="4622971022462973384" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

