<div id="review_2718203051" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2718203051" />
    <a title="Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6202132-scott"><img alt="Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531237754p2/6202132.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2718203051?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott" href="/user/show/6202132-scott">Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2718203051" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14733702418893234005">Monotonous prose. Every character sounds like every other character. Stilted, stereotyped, and preciously simple - presumably to evoke the ethereal experience of life in “The Samurai’s Garden.” (WTF do samurai have to do with this story?) Apart from an almost throwaway revelation near the end, this novel is as shallow and unmemorable as an article in an in-flight magazine. Thank God the word “Zen” does not appear in the text. It really reads as if a nice California lady read a couple of Wikipedi</span>
  <span id="freeText14733702418893234005" style="display:none">Monotonous prose. Every character sounds like every other character. Stilted, stereotyped, and preciously simple - presumably to evoke the ethereal experience of life in “The Samurai’s Garden.” (WTF do samurai have to do with this story?) Apart from an almost throwaway revelation near the end, this novel is as shallow and unmemorable as an article in an in-flight magazine. Thank God the word “Zen” does not appear in the text. It really reads as if a nice California lady read a couple of Wikipedia articles about Japan (and Japanese gardens!) and decided to write a book.<br /><br />The seemingly random littering of Japanese words throughout the book made me wonder - again - WTF the author is trying to accomplish? Special annoyance points for the consistent misspelling of “genkan” and the narrator’s referring to himself, at least once, as “Stephen-san.”<br /><br />Then there’s the girl who commits “seppuku” with her father’s fishing knife... Does the author think seppuku just means suicide? Or did the teenage girl ritually eviscerate herself like a samurai warrior?<br /><br />Also, would a Hong Kong Chinese family send their tubercular teenage son to stay in Japan, for his health, in the late 1930’s? AND this boy - without hesitation or comment - kisses and makes love to a Japanese girl (when his own beloved sister isn’t allowed to be in the same room with him, for her own safety)? What am I supposed to think?</span>
  <a data-text-id="14733702418893234005" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


